The reason for this thread is that I Edna’s story shows the kindness of strangers providing her with a safe home, clothing and food, as well as a friendship that lasted a lifetime. And Anne’s story shows how terrifying it was growing up surrounded by war, at risk of death

Now meet Anne my paternal grandmother she is almost 91 and lived in Sunderland also just a child during g the war, living very close to the docks, a story that stuck out was when she was out playing and a Nazi plane fired with the shells falling all around her, https://t.co/O43Kx5iffQ
When she ran to an air raid shelter.

And she would visit them for holidays right up until she was diagnosed with vascular dementia. One of my biggest memories is that she kept her doll and teddy from her childhood the doll had a missing eye and a crack in its China head, which she told me happened

Weapon manufacturing. My Nan was an only child. She told me how terrified she was but also how lucky she was to be placed with such a lovely family in wales. A family whom for many years after she kept in touch with, they even stayed at my Nan’s when I was child,

So here it goes meet Edna my maternal grandmother. She was born in 1933, when #ww2 broke out she was evacuated to wales, this was due to how dangerous London was and there was no one to take care of her, her aunts in London all worked at the #woolwicharsenal helping with https://t.co/j3tobdQ6D8
So anyway the #Ukriane has made me think about the stories they told me (one of them still tells me her experiences as she is still alive and nearing 91)

Both my grandmothers were children of World War Two. One was born in eltham south east London. The other Born in Sunderland. One was evacuated to wales and the other had to stay out and even was shot at by a Nazi plane. Both told me their stories and one continues to do so.
